The Weinstein Company had been in an active sale process as it tried to preserve assets and jobs but to no avail. NEW YORK - The New York studio co-founded by disgraced movie producer Harvey Weinstein will file for bankruptcy after talks to sell its assets to investors failed. Weinstein faces dozens of sexual abuse allegations, which he has denied. The Weinstein company had been in an active sale process as it tried to preserve assets and jobs but to no avail. Two weeks ago, the New York Attorney General’s office filed a lawsuit against the company, alleging senior executives failed to prevent the mistreatment of staff by Weinstein, this dealt The Weinstein Company a final blow. The company’s directors say now declaring bankruptcy is the only viable option to "maximise the company’s remaining value".